# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: xmpp-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Unlike most commercial instant messaging protocols, XMPP is defined in an open standard in the application layer.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The architecture of the XMPP network is similar to email; anyone can run their own XMPP server and there is no central master server.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] This federated open system approach allows users to interoperate with others on any server using a Jabber identifier (JID) user account, similar to an email address.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] XMPP implementations can be developed using any software license and many server, client, and library implementations are distributed as free and open-source software.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Numerous freeware and commercial software implementations also exist.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Originally developed by the open-source community, the protocols were formalized as an approved instant messaging standard in 2004 and have been continuously developed with new extensions and features.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Various XMPP client software are available on both desktop and mobile platforms and devices – by 2003 the protocol was used by over ten million people worldwide on the network, according to the XMPP Standards Foundation.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Although the protocol has other uses, the primary application is Federated Instant Messaging, to deliver a standard Instant Messaging and Presence Protocol, outlined below.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] A client Alice ("alice@example.com") has a message for some other user, Beth ("beth@example.com"), and uses XMPP to convey this to the example.com server.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] If Beth is online, the server delivers the message instantly, otherwise it will be held for delivery later.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] If Beth is offline, this status is visible to Alice.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] If the message is for a user on another server, Charles ("charles@example.**net**"), then the example.**com** server connects using XMPP to pass the message to the example.**net** server.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The message is then similarly delivered or held, and Alice is informed of the status.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Following the initial message delivery, the end clients are in a "chat" and each party is subsequently informed of changes to the other's status.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The XMPP client communicates with the server over a TLS-encrypted TCP stream on port 5222.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] XMPP servers communicate with each other over a TLS-encrypted TCP stream on port 5269.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The XMPP network architecture is reminiscent of the Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP), a client–server model; clients do not talk directly to one another as it is decentralized – anyone can run a server.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] By design, there is no central authoritative server as there is with messaging services such as AIM, WLM, WhatsApp or Telegram.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Some confusion often arises on this point as there is a public XMPP server being run at `jabber.org`, to which many users subscribe.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] However, anyone may run their own XMPP server on their own domain.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Every user on the network has a unique XMPP address, called *Jabber ID*.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The JID is structured like an email address with a username and a domain name (or IP address) for the server where that user resides, separated by an at sign (`@`) – for example, “`alice@example.com`“: here `alice` is the username and `example.com` the server with which the user is registered.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Since a user may wish to log in from multiple locations, they may specify a **resource**.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] A resource identifies a particular client belonging to the user (for example home, work, or mobile).
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] This may be included in the JID by appending a slash followed by the name of the resource.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] For example, the full JID of a user's mobile account could be `username@example.com/mobile`.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Each resource may have specified a numerical value called **priority**.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Messages simply sent to `username@example.com` will go to the client with highest priority, but those sent to `username@example.com/mobile` will go *only* to the mobile client.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The highest priority is the one with largest numerical value.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] JIDs without a username part are also valid, and may be used for system messages and control of special features on the server.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] A resource remains optional for these JIDs as well.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The means to route messages based on a logical endpoint identifier—the JID, instead of by an explicit IP address—presents opportunities to use XMPP as an overlay network implementation on top of different underlying networks.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The original and "native" transport protocol for XMPP is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), using open-ended XML streams over long-lived TCP connections.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] As an alternative to the TCP transport, the XMPP community has also developed an HTTP transport for web clients as well as users behind restricted firewalls.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] In the original specification, XMPP could use HTTP in two ways: *polling* and *binding*.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The polling method, now deprecated, essentially implies messages stored on a server-side database are being fetched (and posted) regularly by an XMPP client by way of HTTP 'GET' and 'POST' requests.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The binding method, implemented using *Bidirectional-streams Over Synchronous HTTP* (BOSH), allows servers to push messages to clients as soon as they are sent.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] This push model of notification is more efficient than polling, where many of the polls return no new data.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] XMPP also supports using WebSockets to communicate to a server.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Because the client uses HTTP, most firewalls allow clients to fetch and post messages without any hindrances.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Thus, in scenarios where the TCP port used by XMPP is blocked, a server can listen on the normal HTTP port and the traffic should pass without problems.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Various websites let people sign into XMPP via a browser.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Furthermore, there are open public servers that listen on standard http (port 80) and https (port 443) ports, and hence allow connections from behind most firewalls.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] However, the IANA-registered port for BOSH is actually 5280, not 80.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The XMPP Standards Foundation or XSF (formerly the Jabber Software Foundation) is active in developing open XMPP extensions, so called *XEPs*.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] However, extensions can also be defined by any individual, software project, or organization.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] To maintain interoperability, common extensions are managed by the XSF.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] XMPP applications beyond IM include: chat rooms, network management, content syndication, collaboration tools, file sharing, gaming, remote systems control and monitoring, geolocation, middleware and cloud computing, VoIP, and identity services.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Building on its capability to support discovery across local network domains, XMPP is well-suited for cloud computing where virtual machines, networks, and firewalls would otherwise present obstacles to alternative service discovery and presence-based solutions.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Cloud computing and storage systems rely on various forms of communication over multiple levels, including not only messaging between systems to relay state but also the migration or distribution of larger objects, such as storage or virtual machines.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Along with authentication and in-transit data protection, XMPP can be applied at a variety of levels and may prove ideal as an extensible middleware or Message-oriented middleware (MOM) protocol.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Since XML is text based, normal XMPP has a higher network overhead compared to purely binary solutions.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] This issue was being addressed by the experimental XEP-0322 Efficient XML Interchange (EXI) Format, where XML is serialized in an efficient binary manner, especially in schema-informed mode.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] In-band binary data transfer is limited.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Binary data must be first base64 encoded before it can be transmitted in-band.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Therefore, any significant amount of binary data (e.g., file transfers) is best transmitted out-of-band, using in-band messages to coordinate.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] In most cases this is dealt with by using an attachment to a message and the widely implemented XEP-0363 HTTP File Upload mechanism.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Voice and Video chat can be done via the Jingle XMPP Extension Protocol, XEP-0166.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Using the extension called Jingle, XMPP can provide an open means to support machine-to-machine or peer-to-peer communications across a diverse set of networks.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] This feature is mainly used for IP telephony (VoIP).
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] XMPP supports conferences with multiple users, using the specification Multi-User Chat (MUC) (XEP-0045).
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] From the point of view of a normal user, it is comparable to Internet Relay Chat (IRC).
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] XMPP servers can be isolated (e.g., on a company intranet), and secure authentication (SASL) and point-to-point encryption (TLS) have been built into the core XMPP specifications.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Off-the-Record Messaging (OTR) is an extension of XMPP enabling encryption of messages and data.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] It has since been replaced by a better extension, multi-end-to-multi-end encryption (OMEMO, XEP-0384) end-to-end encryption between users.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] This gives a higher level of security, by encrypting all data from the source client and decrypting again at the target client; the server operator cannot decrypt the data they are forwarding.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Messages can also be encrypted with OpenPGP, for example with the software Gajim.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] While several service discovery protocols exist today (such as zeroconf or the Service Location Protocol), XMPP provides a solid base for the discovery of services residing locally or across a network, and the availability of these services (via presence information), as specified by XEP-0030 DISCO.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] One of the original design goals of the early Jabber open-source community was enabling users to connect to multiple instant messaging systems (especially non-XMPP systems) through a single client application.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] This was done through entities called *transports* or *gateways* to other instant messaging protocols like ICQ, AIM or Yahoo Messenger, but also to protocols such as SMS, IRC or email.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Unlike multi-protocol clients, XMPP provides this access at the server level by communicating via special gateway services running alongside an XMPP server.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Any user can "register" with one of these gateways by providing the information needed to log on to that network, and can then communicate with users of that network as though they were XMPP users.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Thus, such gateways function as client proxies (the gateway authenticates on the user's behalf on the non-XMPP service).
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] As a result, any client that fully supports XMPP can access any network with a gateway without extra code in the client, and without the need for the client to have direct access to the Internet.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Another type of gateway is a server-to-server gateway, which enables a non-XMPP server deployment to connect to native XMPP servers using the built in interdomain federation features of XMPP.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] XMPP is implemented by many clients, servers, and code libraries.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] These implementations are provided under a variety of software licenses.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Numerous XMPP server software exist, some well known ones include ejabberd and Prosody.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] A large number of XMPP client software exist on various modern and legacy platforms, including both graphical and command line based clients.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] According to the XMPP website, some of the most popular software include Conversations, Cheogram, Monocles and Quicksy (Android), Dino (BSD, Windows, Unix, Linux), Converse.js (web browser, Linux, Windows, macOS), Gajim (Windows, Linux), Monal (macOS, iOS), and Swift.IM (macOS, Windows, Linux).
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Lately, Monal has been forked as a Quicksy release for iOS.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Other clients include: Bombus, ChatSecure, Coccinella, Miranda NG, Pidgin, Psi, Tkabber, Trillian, and Xabber.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] There are thousands of XMPP servers worldwide, many public ones as well as private individuals or organizations running their own servers without commercial intent.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Numerous websites show a list of public XMPP servers where users may register at (for example on the XMPP.net website).
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Several large public IM services natively use or used XMPP, including LiveJournal's "LJ Talk", Nimbuzz, and HipChat.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Various hosting services, such as DreamHost, enable hosting customers to choose XMPP services alongside more traditional web and email services.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Specialized XMPP hosting services also exist in form of cloud so that domain owners need not directly run their own XMPP servers, including Cisco Webex Connect, Chrome.pl, Flosoft.biz, i-pobox.net, and hosted.im.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The majority of these services are Federated – so that users of one service can communicate with users of another service.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] XMPP is also used in deployments of non-IM services, including smart grid systems such as demand response applications, message-oriented middleware, and as a replacement for SMS to provide text messaging on many smartphone clients.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Some of the largest messaging providers use, or have been using, various forms of XMPP based protocols in their backend systems without necessarily exposing this fact to their end users.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] One example is Google, which in August 2005 introduced Google Talk, a combination VoIP and IM system that uses XMPP for instant messaging and as a base for a voice and file transfer signaling protocol called Jingle.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The initial launch did not include server-to-server communications; Google enabled that feature on January 17, 2006.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Google later added video functionality to Google Talk, also using the Jingle protocol for signaling.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] In May 2013, Google announced XMPP compatibility would be dropped from Google Talk for server-to-server federation, although it would retain client-to-server support.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Google Talk has since been dropped from Google's line of products.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] In January 2008, AOL introduced experimental XMPP support for its AOL Instant Messenger (AIM) service, allowing AIM users to communicate using XMPP.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] However, in March 2008, this service was discontinued.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] As of May 2011, AOL offers limited XMPP support.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] In February 2010, the social-networking site Facebook opened up its chat feature to third-party applications via XMPP.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Some functionality was unavailable through XMPP, and support was dropped in April 2014.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] In 2024, in response to EU Digital Markets Act Meta were compelled to enable a higher degree of interoperability between their products WhatsApp and Facebook Messenger (both closed XMPP implementations) and other XMPP systems.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] This describes a possible route for third parties to interoperate with Meta XMPP products, which is a much lower level of interoperability than true Federation.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Similarly, in December 2011, Microsoft released an XMPP interface to its Microsoft Messenger service.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Skype, its de facto successor, also provided limited XMPP support.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] XMPP is the de facto standard for private chat in gaming related platforms such as Origin, and PlayStation, as well as the now discontinued Xfire and Raptr.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Two notable exceptions are Steam and Xbox LIVE; both use their own proprietary messaging protocols.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Jeremie Miller began working on the Jabber technology in 1998 and released the first version of the `jabberd` server on January 4, 1999.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The early Jabber community focused on open-source software, mainly the jabberd server, but its major outcome proved to be the development of the XMPP protocol.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) formed an XMPP working group in 2002 to formalize the core protocols as an IETF instant messaging and presence technology.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The early Jabber protocol, as developed in 1999 and 2000, formed the basis for XMPP as published in RFC 3920 and RFC 3921 in October 2004 (the primary changes during formalization by the IETF's XMPP Working Group were the addition of TLS for channel encryption and SASL for authentication).
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The XMPP Working group also produced specifications RFC 3922 and RFC 3923.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] In 2011, RFC 3920 and RFC 3921 were superseded by RFC 6120 and RFC 6121 respectively, with RFC 6122 specifying the XMPP address format.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] In addition to these core protocols standardized at the IETF, the XMPP Standards Foundation (formerly the Jabber Software Foundation) is active in developing open XMPP extensions.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The first IM service based on XMPP was Jabber.org, which has operated continuously and offered free accounts since 1999.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] From 1999 until February 2006, the service used jabberd as its server software, at which time it migrated to ejabberd (both of which are free software application servers).
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] In January 2010, the service migrated to the proprietary M-Link server software produced by Isode Ltd.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] In September 2008, Cisco Systems acquired Jabber, Inc., the creators of the commercial product Jabber XCP.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The XMPP Standards Foundation (XSF) develops and publishes extensions to XMPP through a standards process centered on *XMPP Extension Protocols* (XEPs, previously known as Jabber Enhancement Proposals or JEPs).
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] XMPP features such as federation across domains, publish/subscribe, authentication and its security even for mobile endpoints are being used to implement the Internet of Things.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] Several XMPP extensions are part of the experimental implementation: Efficient XML Interchange (EXI) Format; Sensor Data; Provisioning; Control; Concentrators; Discovery.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] These efforts are documented on a page in the XMPP wiki dedicated to Internet of Things and the XMPP IoT mailing list.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] XMPP has often been regarded as a competitor to SIMPLE, based on Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), as the standard protocol for instant messaging and presence notification.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The XMPP extension for multi-user chat can be seen as a competitor to IRC, although IRC is far simpler, has far fewer features, and is far more widely used.
[src:xmpp-protocol/extensible-messaging-and-presence-protocol] The XMPP extensions for publish–subscribe provide many of the same features as the Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP).
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] A **federated identity** in information technology is the means of linking a person's electronic identity and attributes, stored across multiple distinct identity management systems.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Federated identity is related to single sign-on (SSO), in which a user's single authentication ticket, or token, is trusted across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and is understood on the level of technical interoperability, and it would not be possible without some sort of federation.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] In information technology (IT), federated identity management (FIdM) amounts to having a common set of policies, practices and protocols in place to manage the identity and trust into IT users and devices across organizations.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Single sign-on (SSO) systems allow a single user authentication process across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and technical interoperability.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Centralized identity management solutions were created to help deal with user and data security where the user and the systems they accessed were within the same network – or at least the same "domain of control".
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Increasingly, however, users are accessing external systems which are fundamentally outside their domain of control, and external users are accessing internal systems.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] The increasingly common separation of the user from the systems requiring access is an inevitable by-product of the decentralization brought about by the integration of the Internet into every aspect of both personal and business life.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Evolving identity management challenges, and especially the challenges associated with cross-company, cross-domain access, have given rise to a new approach to identity management, known now as "federated identity management".
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] FIdM, or the "federation" of identity, describes the technologies, standards and use-cases which serve to enable the portability of identity information across otherwise autonomous security domains.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] The ultimate goal of identity federation is to enable users of one domain to securely access data or systems of another domain seamlessly, and without the need for completely redundant user administration.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Identity federation comes in many flavors, including "user-controlled" or "user-centric" scenarios, as well as enterprise-controlled or business-to-business scenarios.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Federation is enabled through the use of open industry standards and/or openly published specifications, such that multiple parties can achieve interoperability for common use-cases.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Typical use-cases involve things such as cross-domain, web-based single sign-on, cross-domain user account provisioning, cross-domain entitlement management and cross-domain user attribute exchange.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Use of identity federation standards can reduce cost by eliminating the need to scale one-off or proprietary solutions.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] It can increase security and lower risk by enabling an organization to identify and authenticate a user once, and then use that identity information across multiple systems, including external partner websites.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] It can improve privacy compliance by allowing the user to control what information is shared, or by limiting the amount of information shared.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] And lastly, it can drastically improve the end-user experience by eliminating the need for new account registration through automatic "federated provisioning" or the need to redundantly login through cross-domain single sign-on.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] The notion of identity federation is extremely broad, and also evolving.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] It could involve user-to-user and user-to-application as well as application-to-application use-case scenarios at both the browser tier and the web services or service-oriented architecture (SOA) tier.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] It can involve high-trust, high-security scenarios as well as low-trust, low-security scenarios.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] The levels of identity assurance that may be required for a given scenario are also being standardized through a common and open Identity Assurance Framework.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] It can involve user-centric use-cases, as well as enterprise-centric use-cases.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] The term "identity federation" is by design a generic term, and is not bound to any one specific protocol, technology, implementation or company.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Identity federations may be bi-lateral relationships or multilateral relationships.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] In the latter case, the multilateral federation frequently occurs in a vertical market, such as in law enforcement (such as the National Identity Exchange Federation - NIEF), and research and education (such as InCommon).
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] If the identity federation is bilateral, the two parties can exchange the necessary metadata (assertion signing keys, etc.) to implement the relationship.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] In a multilateral federation, the metadata exchange among participants is a more complex issue.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] It can be handled in a hub-and-spoke exchange or by the distribution of a metadata aggregate by a federated operator.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] One thing that is consistent, however, is the fact that "federation" describes methods of identity portability which are achieved in an open, often standards-based manner – meaning anyone adhering to the open specification or standard can achieve the full spectrum of use-cases and interoperability.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Identity federation can be accomplished any number of ways, some of which involve the use of formal Internet standards, such as the OASIS Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) specification, and some of which may involve open-source technologies and/or other openly published specifications (e.g.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Information Cards, OpenID, the Higgins trust framework or Novell's Bandit project).
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Technologies used for federated identity include SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language), OAuth, OpenID, Security Tokens (Simple Web Tokens, JSON Web Tokens, and SAML assertions), Web Service Specifications, and Windows Identity Foundation.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] The Federal Risk and Authorization Management Program (FedRAMP) is a government-wide program that provides a standardized approach to security assessment, authorization, and continuous monitoring for cloud products and services.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] The FedRAMP program supports the transition of federal agencies from legacy IT infrastructure to cloud-based computing environments.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Here is a list of services that provide social login features which they encourage other websites to use.
[src:xmpp-protocol/federated-identity] Related are federated identity login providers.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging was pioneered in the early Internet era; the IRC protocol was the earliest to achieve wide adoption.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Later in the 1990s, ICQ was among the first closed and commercialized instant messengers, and several rival services appeared afterwards as it became a popular use of the Internet.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Beginning with its first introduction in 2005, BlackBerry Messenger became the first popular example of mobile-based IM, combining features of traditional IM and mobile SMS.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging remains very popular today; IM apps are the most widely used smartphone apps: in 2018 for instance there were 980 million monthly active users of WeChat and 1.3 billion monthly users of WhatsApp, the largest IM network.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging (IM), sometimes also called "messaging" or "texting", consists of computer-based human communication between two users (private messaging) or more (chat room or "group") in real-time, allowing immediate receipt of acknowledgment or reply.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] This is in direct contrast to email, where conversations are not in real-time, and the perceived quasi-synchrony of the communications by the users (although many systems allow users to send offline messages that the other user receives when logging in).
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Earlier IM networks were limited to text-based communication, not dissimilar to mobile text messaging.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] As technology has moved forward, IM has expanded to include voice calling using a microphone, videotelephony using webcams, file transfer, location sharing, image and video transfer, voice notes, and other features.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] IM is conducted over the Internet or other types of networks (see also LAN messenger).
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Depending on the IM protocol, the technical architecture can be peer-to-peer (direct point-to-point transmission) or client–server (when all clients have to first connect to the central server).
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Primary IM services are controlled by their corresponding companies and usually follow the client-server model.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] At one point, the term "Instant Messenger" was a service mark of AOL Time Warner and could not be used in software not affiliated with AOL in the United States.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] For this reason, in April 2007, the instant messaging client formerly named Gaim (or gaim) announced that they would be renamed "Pidgin".
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Modern IM services generally provide their own client, either a separately installed application or a browser-based client.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] They are normally centralised networks run by the servers of the platform's operators, unlike peer-to-peer protocols like XMPP.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] These usually only work within the same IM network, although some allow limited function with other services (see #Interoperability).
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Third-party client software applications exist that will connect with most of the major IM services.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] There is the class of instant messengers that uses the serverless model, which doesn't require servers, and the IM network consists only of clients.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] There are several serverless messengers: RetroShare, Tox, Bitmessage, Ricochet.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Some examples of popular IM services today include Signal, Telegram, WhatsApp Messenger, WeChat, QQ Messenger, Viber, Line, and Snapchat.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] The popularity of certain apps greatly differ between different countries.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Certain apps have an emphasis on certain uses - for example, Skype focuses on video calling, Slack focuses on messaging and file sharing for work teams, and Snapchat focuses on image messages.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Some social networking services offer messaging services as a component of their overall platform, such as Facebook's Facebook Messenger, who also own WhatsApp.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Others have a direct IM function as an additional adjunct component of their social networking platforms, like Instagram, Reddit, Tumblr, TikTok, Clubhouse and Twitter; this also includes for example dating websites, such as OkCupid or Plenty of Fish, and online gaming chat platforms.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Private chat allows users to converse privately with another person or a group.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Privacy can also be enhanced in several ways, such as end-to-end encryption by default.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Public and group chat features allow users to communicate with multiple people simultaneously.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Many major IM services and applications offer a call feature for user-to-user voice calls, conference calls, and voice messages.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] The call functionality is useful for professionals who utilize the application for work purposes and as a hands-free method.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Videotelephony using a webcam is also possible by some.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Some IM applications include in-app games for entertainment.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Messenger, for example, introduced these where users could play a game and viewed by friends in real-time.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] MSN Messenger featured a number of playable games within the interface.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Facebook's Messenger has had a built-in option to play games with people in a chat, including games like Tetris and Blackjack.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Discord features multiple games built inside the "activities" tab in voice channels.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] A relatively new feature to instant messaging, peer-to-peer payments are available for financial tasks on top of communication.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] The lack of a service fee also makes these advantageous to financial applications.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] IM services such as Facebook Messenger and the WeChat 'super-app' for example offer a payment feature.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Though the term dates from the 1990s, instant messaging predates the Internet, first appearing on multi-user operating systems like Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS) and Multiplexed Information and Computing Service (Multics) in the mid-1960s.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Initially, some of these systems were used as notification systems for services like printing, but quickly were used to facilitate communication with other users logged into the same machine.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] CTSS facilitated communication via text message for up to 30 people.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Parallel to instant messaging were early online chat facilities, the earliest of which was Talkomatic (1973) on the PLATO system, which allowed 5 people to chat simultaneously on a 512 x 512 plasma display (5 lines of text + 1 status line per person).
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] During the bulletin board system (BBS) phenomenon that peaked during the 1980s, some systems incorporated chat features which were similar to instant messaging; Freelancin' Roundtable was one prime example.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] The first such general-availability commercial online chat service (as opposed to PLATO, which was educational) was the CompuServe CB Simulator in 1980, created by CompuServe executive Alexander "Sandy" Trevor in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] As networks developed, the protocols spread with the networks.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Some of these used a peer-to-peer protocol (e.g. talk, ntalk and ytalk), while others required peers to connect to a server (see talker and IRC).
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] The Zephyr Notification Service (still in use at some institutions) was invented at MIT's Project Athena in the 1980s to allow service providers to locate and send messages to users.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Early instant messaging programs were primarily real-time text, where characters appeared as they were typed.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] This includes the Unix "talk" command line program, which was popular in the 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Celerity BBS) also used a similar interface.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Modern implementations of real-time text also exist in instant messengers, such as AOL's Real-Time IM as an optional feature.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] As such, it could be considered a type of graphical user interface (GUI), albeit much more primitive than the later Unix, Windows and Macintosh based GUI IM software.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] OLMs were what Q-Link called "Plus Services" meaning they charged an extra per-minute fee on top of the monthly Q-Link access costs.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Development of the Internet Relay Chat (IRC) protocol began in 1988, and this would become the Internet's first widespread instant messaging standard.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Modern, Internet-wide, GUI-based messaging clients as they are known today, began to take off in the mid-1990s with PowWow, ICQ, and AOL Instant Messenger (AIM).
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Similar functionality was offered by CU-SeeMe in 1992; though primarily an audio/video chat link, users could also send textual messages to each other.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] AOL later acquired Mirabilis, the authors of ICQ; establishing dominance in the instant messaging market.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] A few years later ICQ (then owned by AOL) was awarded two patents for instant messaging by the U.S. patent office.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Meanwhile, other companies developed their own software; (Excite, Microsoft (MSN), Ubique, and Yahoo!), each with its own proprietary protocol and client; users therefore had to run multiple client applications if they wished to use more than one of these networks.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] However, the open protocol IRC continued to be popular by the millennium, and its most popular graphical app was mIRC.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] While instant messaging was mainly in use for consumer recreational purposes, in 1998, IBM launched their Lotus Sametime instant messenger software, the first popular example of enterprise-grade instant messaging.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] In 2000, an open-source application and open standards-based protocol called Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol (XMPP) was launched, initially branded as *Jabber*.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] XMPP servers could act as gateways to other IM protocols, reducing the need to run multiple clients.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Video calling using a webcam also started taking off during this time.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Microsoft's NetMeeting, which was focused on business "web conferencing", was one of the earliest; the company then launched Windows Messenger, coming preloaded on Windows XP, featuring video capabilities.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Messenger added video capabilities in 2001; by 2005, such features were built-in also in AIM, MSN Messenger, and Skype.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] There were a reported 100 million users of instant messaging in 2001.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] As of 2003, AIM was the globally most popular instant messenger with 195 million users and exchanges of 1.6 billion messages daily.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] By 2006, AIM controlled 52 percent of the instant messaging market, but rapidly declined shortly thereafter as the company struggled to compete with other services.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging integrated in other services started picking up pace in the late 2000s.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Myspace, the then-largest social networking service, launched Myspace IM in 2006, shortly after Google's Gtalk, which was integrated into its Gmail webmail interface.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Facebook Chat launched in 2008, providing IM to users of the social network.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] By 2010, traditional instant messaging was in sharp decline in favor of these new messaging features on wider social networks, which at the time were not normally called IM.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] For instance, AIM's userbase had declined by more than half throughout the year 2011.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Standalone instant messenger services were revived, evolving into becoming primarily being used on mobile due to the increasing use of Internet-enabled cell phones and smartphones.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Mobile instant messaging surpassed SMS in global message volume by 2013.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] While SMS relied on traditional paid telephone services, IM apps on mobile were available for free or a minor data charge.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Older IM services were eventually shut, including AIM and Yahoo!
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Messenger, and also Windows Live Messenger, which merged into Skype in 2013.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] In 2014, it was reported that instant messaging had more users than social networks.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Concurrently, rising use of instant messaging at workplaces led to the creation of new services (enterprise application integration (EAI)) often integrated with other enterprise applications such as workflow systems, for example in Skype for Business, Slack and Microsoft Teams.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Meanwhile, the launch of Discord in 2015 has marked a notable new example of traditional IM originally designed for desktops.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Most IM protocols are proprietary and are not designed to be interoperable with others, meaning that many IM networks have been incompatible and users have been unable to reach users on other networks.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] As of 2024, fragmentation of IM services means that a typical user is likely to have to use more networks than ever, including the need to download the apps and signing up, to stay in touch with all their contacts.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] However, there had been attempts for solutions.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Multi-protocol clients can use any of the IM protocols by using additional local libraries for each protocol.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Examples of multi-protocol instant messenger software include Pidgin and Trillian, and more recently Beeper.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] These third-party clients have often been unable to keep up due to proprietary protocol restrictions and getting locked out of it.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] For instance, in 2015, WhatsApp started banning users who were using unofficial clients.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Major IM providers usually cite the need for formal agreements, and security concerns as reasons for making changes.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] In the early 2000s, when instant messaging was quickly growing, most attempts at producing a unified standard for the-then major IM providers (AOL, Yahoo!, Microsoft) had failed.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] There was a "bitter row" between AOL and its rivals regarding the opening up of their networks.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] In 2000, U.S. regulatory Federal Communications Commission (FCC) proposed, and supported by Microsoft chairman Bill Gates, that AOL providing interoperability of its AIM and ICQ instant messengers with Microsoft's MSN Messenger was a condition for the forthcoming AOL-Time Warner merger.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] However, in 2004, Microsoft, Yahoo! and AOL agreed to a deal in which Microsoft's enterprise IM server Live Communications Server 2005 would have the possibility to talk to their rival counterparts and vice versa.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] On October 13, 2005, Microsoft and Yahoo! announced that their IM networks would soon be interoperable, using SIP/SIMPLE.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] This was finally rolled out to Windows Live Messenger and Yahoo!
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Additionally, in December 2005 by the AOL and Google strategic partnership deal, it was announced that AIM and ICQ users would be able to communicate with Google Talk users.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] However this feature took until December 2007 to roll out.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] XMPP provided the best example of open protocol interoperability, having had gateways that connected to Google Talk, Lotus Sametime and others.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Later, RCS was developed by telecommunication companies as an instant messaging protocol to replace SMS under a unified standard.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] In 2022, the European Union passed the Digital Markets Act, which largely came into effect in early 2023.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Among other things, the legislation mandates certain interoperability between the largest IM platforms in use in Europe.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] As a result, in March 2024, Meta Platforms opened up its WhatsApp and Messenger networks to be interoperable.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Some approaches allow organizations to deploy their own, private instant messaging network by enabling them to restrict access to the server (often with the IM network entirely behind their firewall) and administer user permissions.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Other corporate messaging systems allow registered users to also connect from outside the corporation LAN, by using an encrypted, firewall-friendly, HTTPS-based protocol.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Usually, a dedicated corporate IM server has several advantages, such as pre-populated contact lists, integrated authentication, and better security and privacy.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging has changed how people communicate in the workplace.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Enterprise messaging applications like Slack, Symphony, Teamnote and Yammer allow companies to enforce policies on how employees message at work and ensure secure storage of sensitive data.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] They allow employees to separate work information from their personal emails and texts.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Messaging applications may make workplace communication efficient, but they can also have consequences on productivity.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] A study at Slack showed on average, people spend 10 hours a day on Slack, which is about 67% more time than they spend using email.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging is implemented in many video-conferencing tools.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] A study of chat use during work-related videoconferencing found that chat during meetings allows participants to communicate without interrupting the meeting, plan action around common resources, and enables greater inclusion.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] The study also found that chat can cause distractions and information asymmetries between participants.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Users sometimes make use of internet slang or text speak to abbreviate common words or expressions to quicken conversations or reduce keystrokes.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] The language has become widespread, with well-known expressions such as 'lol' translated over to face-to-face language.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Emotions are often expressed in shorthand, such as the abbreviation LOL, BRB and TTYL; respectively laugh(ing) out loud, be right back, and talk to you later.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Some, however, attempt to be more accurate with emotional expression over IM.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Real time reactions such as (*chortle*) (*snort*) (*guffaw*) or (*eye-roll*) have been popular at one point.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Also there are certain standards that are being introduced into mainstream conversations including, '#' indicates the use of sarcasm in a statement and '*' which indicates a spelling mistake and/or grammatical error in the prior message, followed by a correction.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging products can usually be categorised into two types: Enterprise Instant Messaging (EIM) and Consumer Instant Messaging (CIM).
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Enterprise solutions use an internal IM server, however this is not always feasible, particularly for smaller businesses with limited budgets.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] The second option, using a CIM provides the advantage of being inexpensive to implement and has little need for investing in new hardware or server software.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] IM is increasingly becoming a feature of enterprise software rather than a stand-alone application.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Tens of millions of the consumer IM accounts in use are being used for business purposes by employees of companies and other organizations.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] The adoption of IM across corporate networks outside of the control of IT organizations creates risks and liabilities for companies who do not effectively manage and support IM use.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] IM was initially shunned by the corporate world partly due to security concerns, but by 2003 many had started embracing these new services.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] In response to the demand for business-grade IM and the need to ensure security and legal compliance, a new type of instant messaging, called "Enterprise Instant Messaging" ("EIM") was created when Lotus Development launched IBM Lotus Sametime in 1998.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Microsoft followed suit shortly thereafter with Microsoft Exchange Instant Messaging, later created a new platform called Microsoft Office Live Communications Server, and released Office Communications Server 2007 in October 2007.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Oracle Corporation also jumped into the market with its Oracle Beehive unified collaboration software.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Both IBM Lotus and Microsoft have introduced federation between their EIM systems and some of the public IM networks so that employees may use one interface to both their internal EIM system and their contacts on AOL, MSN, and Yahoo.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] As of 2010, leading EIM platforms include IBM Lotus Sametime, Microsoft Office Communications Server, Jabber XCP and Cisco Unified Presence.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Industry-focused EIM platforms such as Reuters Messaging and Bloomberg Messaging also provide IM abilities to financial services companies.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Crackers (malicious or black hat hackers) have consistently used IM networks as vectors for delivering phishing attempts, drive-by URLs, and virus-laden file attachments, with over 1100 discrete attacks listed by the IM Security Center in 2004–2007.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] IM connections sometimes occur in plain text, making them vulnerable to eavesdropping.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Also, IM client software often requires the user to expose open UDP ports to the world, raising the threat posed by potential security vulnerabilities.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] In the early 2000s, a new class of IT security providers emerged to provide remedies for the risks and liabilities faced by corporations who chose to use IM for business communications.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] The IM security providers created new products to be installed in corporate networks for the purpose of archiving, content-scanning, and security-scanning IM traffic moving in and out of the corporation.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Similar to the e-mail filtering vendors, the IM security providers focus on the risks and liabilities described above.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] With the rapid adoption of IM in the workplace, demand for IM security products began to grow in the mid-2000s.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] By 2007, the preferred platform for the purchase of security software had become the "computer appliance", according to IDC, who estimated that by 2008, 80% of network security products would be delivered via an appliance.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] By 2014, however, instant messengers' safety level was still extremely poor.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] According to a scorecard by the Electronic Frontier Foundation, only 7 out of 39 instant messengers received a perfect score.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] In contrast, the most popular instant messengers at the time only attained a score of 2 out of 7.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] A number of studies have shown that IM services are quite vulnerable for providing user privacy.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] In 2023, cybersecurity researchers discovered that numerous malicious "mods" exist of the Telegram instant messenger, which is freely available for download from Google Play.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messages are often logged in a local message history, similar to emails' persistent nature.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] IM networks may store messages with either local-based device storage (e.g.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] WhatsApp, Viber, Line, WeChat, Signal etc. software) or cloud-based server storage provided by the service (e.g.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Telegram, Skype, Facebook Messenger, Google Meet/Chat, Discord, Slack etc.).
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Although cloud-based storage is advertised to offer encrypted messages, it poses an increased risk that the IM provider may have access to the decryption keys and view the user's saved messages.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] This requires users to trust IM servers and providers because messages can generally be accessed by the company.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Companies may be compelled to reveal their user's communication and suspend user accounts for any reason.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] News reports from 2013 revealed that the NSA is not only collecting emails and IM messages but also tracking relationships between senders and receivers of those chats and emails in a process known as metadata collection.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Metadata refers to the data concerned about the chat or email as opposed to contents of messages.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] It may be used to collect valuable information.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] In January 2014, Matthew Campbell and Michael Hurley filed a class-action lawsuit against Facebook for breaching the Electronic Communications Privacy Act.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] They alleged that the information in their supposedly private messages was being read and used to generate profit, specifically "for purposes including but not limited to data mining and user profiling".
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] In corporate use of IM, organizational offerings have become very sophisticated in their security and logging measures.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] An employee or organization member must be granted login credentials and permission to use the messaging system.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Creating a specific account for each user allows the organization to identify, track and record all use of their messenger system on their servers.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Encryption is the primary method that instant messaging apps use to protect user's data privacy and security.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] For corporate use, encryption and conversation archiving are usually regarded as important features due to security concerns.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] There are also a bunch of open source encrypting messengers.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] IM does hold potential advantages over SMS.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Current instant messaging networks that use end-to-end encryption include Signal, WhatsApp, Wire and iMessage.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Signal and iMessage have started using Post-quantum cryptography in September 2023 and April 2024 respectively.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Applications that have been criticized for lacking or poor encryption methods include Telegram and Confide, as both are prone to error or not having encryption enabled by default.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] In addition to the malicious code threat, using instant messaging at work creates a risk of non-compliance with laws and regulations governing electronic communications in businesses.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] In the United States alone, there are over 10,000 laws and regulations related to electronic messaging and records retention.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] The better-known of these include the Sarbanes–Oxley Act, HIPAA, and SEC 17a-3.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Changes to Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, effective December 1, 2006, created a new category for electronic records which may be requested during discovery in legal proceedings.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Most nations also regulate electronic messaging and records retention similarly to the United States.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] The most common regulations related to IM at work involve producing archived business communications to satisfy government or judicial requests under law.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] Many instant messaging communications fall into the category of business communications that must be archived and retrievable.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] There are 25 countries in the world where WhatsApp messenger is not the market leader in IM, such as the United States, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Denmark, Norway, Sweden, Hungary, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia, Philippines, and China.
[src:xmpp-protocol/instant-messaging] IM apps have varying levels of adoption in different countries.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:xmpp-protocol/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The design goals of XML emphasize simplicity, generality, and usability across the Internet.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] It is a textual data format with strong support via Unicode for different human languages.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Although the design of XML focuses on documents, the language is widely used for the representation of arbitrary data structures, such as those used in web services.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Several schema systems exist to aid in the definition of XML-based languages, while programmers have developed many application programming interfaces (APIs) to aid the processing of XML data.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The main purpose of XML is serialization, i.e. storing, transmitting, and reconstructing arbitrary data.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] For two disparate systems to exchange information, they need to agree upon a file format.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] It is therefore analogous to a lingua franca for representing information.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] As a markup language, XML labels, categorizes, and structurally organizes information.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML tags represent the data structure and contain metadata.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] What is within the tags is data, encoded in the way the XML standard specifies.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] An additional XML schema (XSD) defines the necessary metadata for interpreting and validating XML.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] (This is also referred to as the canonical schema.) An XML document that adheres to basic XML rules is "well-formed"; one that adheres to its schema is "valid".
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] IETF RFC 7303 (which supersedes the older RFC 3023), provides rules for the construction of media types for use in XML message.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] It defines three media types: `application/xml` (`text/xml` is an alias), `application/xml-external-parsed-entity` (`text/xml-external-parsed-entity` is an alias) and `application/xml-dtd`.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] They are used for transmitting raw XML files without exposing their internal semantics.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] RFC 7303 further recommends that XML-based languages be given media types ending in `+xml`, for example, `image/svg+xml` for SVG.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Further guidelines for the use of XML in a networked context appear in RFC 3470, also known as IETF BCP 70, a document covering many aspects of designing and deploying an XML-based language.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML has come into common use for the interchange of data over the Internet.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Hundreds of document formats using XML syntax have been developed, including RSS, Atom, Office Open XML, OpenDocument, SVG, COLLADA, and XHTML.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML also provides the base language for communication protocols such as SOAP and XMPP.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] It is one of the message exchange formats used in the Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) programming technique.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Many industry data standards, such as Health Level 7, OpenTravel Alliance, FpML, MISMO, and the National Information Exchange Model are based on XML and the rich features of the XML schema specification.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] In publishing, Darwin Information Typing Architecture is an XML industry data standard.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML is used extensively to underpin various publishing formats.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] One of the applications of XML in science is the representation of operational meteorology information based on IWXXM standards.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The material in this section is based on the XML Specification.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] This is not an exhaustive list of all the constructs that appear in XML; it provides an introduction to the key constructs most often encountered in day-to-day use.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] character (except Null) may appear in an (1.1) XML document (while some are discouraged).
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The specification places requirements on what an XML processor must do and not do, but the application is outside its scope.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Strings of characters that are not markup are content.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] are classified as markup, while the text between them is classified as content.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] In addition, whitespace before and after the outermost element is classified as markup.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] is a logical document component that either begins with a start-tag and ends with a matching end-tag or consists only of an empty-element tag.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] that exists within a start-tag or empty-element tag.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] , where the names of the attributes are "src" and "alt", and their values are "madonna.jpg" and "Madonna" respectively.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] , where the name of the attribute is "number" and its value is "3".
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] An XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] with some format beyond what XML defines itself.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] that describes some information about themselves.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML documents consist entirely of characters from the Unicode repertoire.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Except for a small number of specifically excluded control characters, any character defined by Unicode may appear within the content of an XML document.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML includes facilities for identifying the *encoding* of the Unicode characters that make up the document, and for expressing characters that, for one reason or another, cannot be used directly.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML 1.1 extends the set of allowed characters to include all the above, plus the remaining characters in the range U+0001–U+001F.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] At the same time, however, it restricts the use of C0 and C1 control characters other than U+0009 (Horizontal Tab), U+000A (Line Feed), U+000D (Carriage Return), and U+0085 (Next Line) by requiring them to be written in escaped form (for example U+0001 must be written as `&#x01;` or its equivalent).
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] In the case of C1 characters, this restriction is a backwards incompatibility; it was introduced to allow common encoding errors to be detected.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The code point U+0000 (Null) is the only character that is not permitted in any XML 1.1 document.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The Unicode character set can be encoded into bytes for storage or transmission in a variety of different ways, called "encodings".
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Unicode itself defines encodings that cover the entire repertoire; well-known ones include UTF-8 (which the XML standard recommends using, without a BOM) and UTF-16.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] There are many other text encodings that predate Unicode, such as ASCII and various ISO/IEC 8859; their character repertoires are in every case subsets of the Unicode character set.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML allows the use of any of the Unicode-defined encodings and any other encodings whose characters also appear in Unicode.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML also provides a mechanism whereby an XML processor can reliably, without any prior knowledge, determine which encoding is being used.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Encodings other than UTF-8 and UTF-16 are not necessarily recognized by every XML parser (and in some cases not even UTF-16, even though the standard mandates it to also be recognized).
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML provides *escape* facilities for including characters that are problematic to include directly.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] All permitted Unicode characters may be represented with a *numeric character reference*.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Consider the Chinese character "中", whose numeric code in Unicode is hexadecimal 4E2D, or decimal 20,013.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] A user whose keyboard offers no method for entering this character could still insert it in an XML document encoded either as `&#20013;` or `&#x4e2d;`.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Similarly, the string "I <3 Jörg" could be encoded for inclusion in an XML document as `I &lt;3 J&#xF6;rg`.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] `&#0;` is not permitted because the null character is one of the control characters excluded from XML, even when using a numeric character reference.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] An alternative encoding mechanism such as Base64 is needed to represent such characters.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Comments may appear anywhere in a document outside other markup.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Comments cannot appear before the XML declaration.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Comments begin with `<!--` and end with `-->`.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] For compatibility with SGML, the string "--" (double-hyphen) is not allowed inside comments; this means comments cannot be nested.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The ampersand has no special significance within comments, so entity and character references are not recognized as such, and there is no way to represent characters outside the character set of the document encoding.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML 1.0 (Fifth Edition) and XML 1.1 support the direct use of almost any Unicode character in element names, attributes, comments, character data, and processing instructions (other than the ones that have special symbolic meaning in XML itself, such as the less-than sign, "<").
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The XML specification defines an XML document as a well-formed text, meaning that it satisfies a list of syntax rules provided in the specification.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The definition of an XML document excludes texts that contain violations of well-formedness rules; they are simply not XML.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] An XML processor that encounters such a violation is required to report such errors and to cease normal processing.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] This policy, occasionally referred to as "draconian error handling", stands in notable contrast to the behavior of programs that process HTML, which are designed to produce a reasonable result even in the presence of severe markup errors.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML's policy in this area has been criticized as a violation of Postel's law ("Be conservative in what you send; be liberal in what you accept").
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The XML specification defines a valid XML document as a well-formed XML document which also conforms to the rules of a Document Type Definition (DTD).
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] In addition to being well formed, an XML document may be *valid*.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] This means that it contains a reference to a Document Type Definition (DTD), and that its elements and attributes are declared in that DTD and follow the grammatical rules for them that the DTD specifies.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML processors are classified as *validating* or *non-validating* depending on whether or not they check XML documents for validity.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] A processor that discovers a validity error must be able to report it, but may continue normal processing.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] A DTD is an example of a *schema* or *grammar*.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Since the initial publication of XML 1.0, there has been substantial work in the area of schema languages for XML.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Such schema languages typically constrain the set of elements that may be used in a document, which attributes may be applied to them, the order in which they may appear, and the allowable parent/child relationships.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The oldest schema language for XML is the document type definition (DTD), inherited from SGML.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] DTD technology is still used in many applications because of its ubiquity.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] A newer schema language, described by the W3C as the successor of DTDs, is XML Schema, often referred to by the initialism for XML Schema instances, XSD (XML Schema Definition).
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XSDs are far more powerful than DTDs in describing XML languages.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] They use a rich datatyping system and allow for more detailed constraints on an XML document's logical structure.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XSDs also use an XML-based format, which makes it possible to use ordinary XML tools to help process them.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] RELAX NG (Regular Language for XML Next Generation) was initially specified by OASIS and is now a standard (Part 2: *Regular-grammar-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] RELAX NG schemas may be written in either an XML based syntax or a more compact non-XML syntax; the two syntaxes are isomorphic and James Clark's conversion tool—Trang—can convert between them without loss of information.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] RELAX NG has a simpler definition and validation framework than XML Schema, making it easier to use and implement.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] It also has the ability to use datatype framework plug-ins; a RELAX NG schema author, for example, can require values in an XML document to conform to definitions in XML Schema Datatypes.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Schematron is a language for making assertions about the presence or absence of patterns in an XML document.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Schematron is now a standard (Part 3: *Rule-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] DSDL (Document Schema Definition Languages) is a multi-part ISO/IEC standard (ISO/IEC 19757) that brings together a comprehensive set of small schema languages, each targeted at specific problems.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] DSDL includes RELAX NG full and compact syntax, Schematron assertion language, and languages for defining datatypes, character repertoire constraints, renaming and entity expansion, and namespace-based routing of document fragments to different validators.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] DSDL schema languages do not have the vendor support of XML Schemas yet, and are to some extent a grassroots reaction of industrial publishers to the lack of utility of XML Schemas for publishing.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Some schema languages not only describe the structure of a particular XML format but also offer limited facilities to influence processing of individual XML files that conform to this format.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] DTDs and XSDs both have this ability; they can for instance provide the infoset augmentation facility and attribute defaults.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] RELAX NG and Schematron intentionally do not provide these.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] A cluster of specifications closely related to XML have been developed, starting soon after the initial publication of XML 1.0.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] It is frequently the case that the term "XML" is used to refer to XML together with one or more of these other technologies that have come to be seen as part of the XML core.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Some other specifications conceived as part of the "XML Core" have failed to find wide adoption, including XInclude, XLink, and XPointer.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The design goals of XML include, "It shall be easy to write programs which process XML documents." Despite this, the XML specification contains almost no information about how programmers might go about doing such processing.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The XML Infoset specification provides a vocabulary to refer to the constructs within an XML document, but does not provide any guidance on how to access this information.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] A variety of APIs for accessing XML have been developed and used, and some have been standardized.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Stream-oriented facilities require less memory and, for certain tasks based on a linear traversal of an XML document, are faster and simpler than other alternatives.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Tree-traversal and data-binding APIs typically require the use of much more memory, but are often found more convenient for use by programmers; some include declarative retrieval of document components via the use of XPath expressions.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XSLT is designed for declarative description of XML document transformations, and has been widely implemented both in server-side packages and Web browsers.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XQuery overlaps XSLT in its functionality, but is designed more for searching of large XML databases.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Simple API for XML (SAX) is a lexical, event-driven API in which a document is read serially and its contents are reported as callbacks to various methods on a handler object of the user's design.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] SAX is fast and efficient to implement, but difficult to use for extracting information at random from the XML, since it tends to burden the application author with keeping track of what part of the document is being processed.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] It is better suited to situations in which certain types of information are always handled the same way, no matter where they occur in the document.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Pull parsing treats the document as a series of items read in sequence using the iterator design pattern.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] A pull parser creates an iterator that sequentially visits the various elements, attributes, and data in an XML document.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Code that uses this iterator can test the current item (to tell, for example, whether it is a start-tag or end-tag, or text), and inspect its attributes (local name, namespace, values of XML attributes, value of text, etc.), and can also move the iterator to the next item.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The code can thus extract information from the document as it traverses it.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The recursive-descent approach tends to lend itself to keeping data as typed local variables in the code doing the parsing, while SAX, for instance, typically requires a parser to manually maintain intermediate data within a stack of elements that are parent elements of the element being parsed.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Pull-parsing code can be more straightforward to understand and maintain than SAX parsing code.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The Document Object Model (DOM) is an interface that allows for navigation of the entire document as if it were a tree of node objects representing the document's contents.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] A DOM document can be created by a parser, or can be generated manually by users (with limitations).
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Data types in DOM nodes are abstract; implementations provide their own programming language-specific bindings.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] DOM implementations tend to be memory intensive, as they generally require the entire document to be loaded into memory and constructed as a tree of objects before access is allowed.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML data binding is a technique for simplifying development of applications that need to work with XML documents.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] It involves mapping the XML document to a hierarchy of strongly typed objects, rather than using the generic objects created by a DOM parser.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The resulting code is often easier to read and maintain, and it can help to identify problems at compile time rather than run-time.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML data binding is particularly well-suited for applications where the document structure is known and fixed at the time the application is written.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] By creating a strongly typed representation of the XML data, developers can take advantage of modern integrated development environments (IDEs) that provide features like auto-complete, code refactoring, and code highlighting.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] This can make it easier to write correct and efficient code, and reduce the risk of errors and bugs.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Example data-binding systems include the Java Architecture for XML Binding (JAXB), XML Serialization in .NET Framework, and XML serialization in gSOAP.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML has appeared as a first-class data type in other languages.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The ECMAScript for XML (E4X) extension to the ECMAScript/JavaScript language explicitly defines two specific objects (XML and XMLList) for JavaScript, which support XML document nodes and XML node lists as distinct objects and use a dot-notation specifying parent-child relationships.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] E4X is supported by the Mozilla 2.5+ browsers (though now deprecated) and Adobe Actionscript but has not been widely adopted.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Similar notations are used in Microsoft's LINQ implementation for Microsoft .NET 3.5 and above, and in Scala (which uses the Java VM).
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The open-source xmlsh application, which provides a Linux-like shell with special features for XML manipulation, similarly treats XML as a data type, using the <[ ]> notation.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The Resource Description Framework defines a data type `rdf:XMLLiteral` to hold wrapped, canonical XML.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Facebook has produced extensions to the PHP and JavaScript languages that add XML to the core syntax in a similar fashion to E4X, namely XHP and JSX respectively.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML is an application profile of SGML (ISO 8879).
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The versatility of SGML for dynamic information display was understood by early digital media publishers in the late 1980s prior to the rise of the Internet.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] By the mid-1990s some practitioners of SGML had gained experience with the then-new World Wide Web, and believed that SGML offered solutions to some of the problems the Web was likely to face as it grew.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Dan Connolly added SGML to the list of W3C's activities when he joined the staff in 1995; work began in mid-1996 when Sun Microsystems engineer Jon Bosak developed a charter and recruited collaborators.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Bosak was well-connected in the small community of people who had experience both in SGML and the Web.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] XML was compiled by a working group of eleven members, supported by a (roughly) 150-member Interest Group.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Technical debate took place on the Interest Group mailing list and issues were resolved by consensus or, when that failed, majority vote of the Working Group.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] A record of design decisions and their rationales was compiled by Michael Sperberg-McQueen on December 4, 1997.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] James Clark served as Technical Lead of the Working Group, notably contributing the empty-element `<empty />` syntax and the name "XML".
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Other names that had been put forward for consideration included "MAGMA" (Minimal Architecture for Generalized Markup Applications), "SLIM" (Structured Language for Internet Markup) and "MGML" (Minimal Generalized Markup Language).
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The co-editors of the specification were originally Tim Bray and Michael Sperberg-McQueen.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Halfway through the project, Bray accepted a consulting engagement with Netscape, provoking vociferous protests from Microsoft.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Bray was temporarily asked to resign the editorship.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] This led to intense dispute in the Working Group, eventually solved by the appointment of Microsoft's Jean Paoli as a third co-editor.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The XML Working Group communicated primarily through email and weekly teleconferences.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] The major design decisions were reached in a short burst of intense work between August and November 1996, when the first Working Draft of an XML specification was published.
[src:xmpp-protocol/xml] Further design work continued through 1997, and XML 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation on February 10, 1998.
